---
// --ask feature section for the landing page.
// "AI" appears exactly twice here and nowhere else on the site.
---

<div class="ask-section">
  <h2>Ask in plain English</h2>

  <p>
    Describe the filter you want. An AI translates it to a deterministic
    expression, shows you what it will run, and asks before running.
  </p>

  <div class="ask-terminal" role="img" aria-label="vcfkit --ask command example">
<span class="t-prompt">$</span> <span class="t-cmd">vcfkit filter --ask \
    "common variants in European populations but rare in African" \
    input.vcf</span>

  <span class="t-label">Query:     </span> <span class="t-cmd">common variants in European populations but rare in African</span>
  <span class="t-label">Expression:</span> <span class="t-expr">INFO/EUR_AF &gt; 0.05 &amp;&amp; INFO/AFR_AF &lt; 0.01</span>
  <span class="t-label">Confidence:</span> <span class="t-conf">95%</span>

<span class="t-prompt2">Run this filter? [Y/n/edit]</span>
  </div>

  <p class="ask-sub">
    Your VCF data never leaves your machine. Only the header schema — field names, types, and
    descriptions — and your query go to the AI. The translator code is open source, so you
    can read exactly what gets sent.
  </p>

  <p class="ask-sub">
    Low-confidence translations (below 50%) require explicit review before running — the gate
    prevents silent wrong results on queries the schema can't fully answer.
  </p>

  <div class="ask-cta">
    <a href="/commands/filter#natural-language-filter---ask" class="btn-secondary">
      Set up ANTHROPIC_API_KEY →
    </a>
  </div>
</div>
